<subSubSection id="C32C6559FA97FF5ACBFFBC1AFF14F944" pageId="242" pageNumber="243" type="description">
<paragraph id="8B8936D2FA97FF5ACBFFBC1AFF14F944" blockId="242.[151,1436,1281,2026]" pageId="242" pageNumber="243">
<emphasis id="B942EAC0FA97FF5ACBFFBC1AFE75FAB0" bold="true" box="[199,413,1281,1306]" pageId="242" pageNumber="243">
Description. 
<emphasis id="B942EAC0FA97FF5ACA5ABC1AFE75FAB0" bold="true" box="[354,413,1281,1306]" italics="true" pageId="242" pageNumber="243">Shell</emphasis>
</emphasis>
very small (
<quantity id="4CCE9B37FA97FF5AC90BBC1AFD78FAB0" box="[563,656,1281,1306]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="7.2" pageId="242" pageNumber="243" unit="mm" value="7.2">7.2 mm</quantity>
), fusiform (W/L = 
<number id="3DFE24F5FA97FF5AC84BBC1AFC5DFAB0" box="[883,949,1281,1306]" pageId="242" pageNumber="243" value="0.361">0.361</number>
), glossy smooth, translucent; of about 
<number id="3DFE24F5FA97FF5ACE41BC1AFA6EFAB3" box="[1401,1414,1281,1305]" pageId="242" pageNumber="243" value="7.0">7</number>
½ strongly convex and moderately elongate whorls, peripheries about mid-whorl, the last about 
<number id="3DFE24F5FA97FF5ACFF6BC3DFB02FA94" box="[1230,1258,1318,1342]" pageId="242" pageNumber="243" value="56.0">56</number>
% of total shell length; suture impressed. Sculptural elements only of ribs; aperture narrow, with a short, wide anterior canal and large spout-like anal sinus. 
<emphasis id="B942EAC0FA97FF5ACAF5BC76FDBBFA2C" bold="true" box="[461,595,1389,1414]" italics="true" pageId="242" pageNumber="243">Protoconch</emphasis>
of 
<number id="3DFE24F5FA97FF5AC942BC75FD60FA2C" box="[634,648,1390,1414]" pageId="242" pageNumber="243" value="2.0">2</number>
smooth glossy whorls, the beginning of the first slightly imbedded in the last whorl such that the spire tip appears blunt. 
<emphasis id="B942EAC0FA97FF5AC9EBBC8AFC6BFA00" bold="true" box="[723,899,1425,1450]" italics="true" pageId="242" pageNumber="243">Axial sculpture</emphasis>
of low, opisthocline ribs, about as wide as their interspaces, obsolete on shoulder near suture and fade just below whorl periphery, before suture of succeeding whorl. Rib crests are round. The base of the last whorl is smooth, without ribs. Growth striae microscopic. 
<emphasis id="B942EAC0FA97FF5ACE65BCC2FA70FA58" bold="true" box="[1373,1432,1497,1522]" italics="true" pageId="242" pageNumber="243">Varix</emphasis>
obscure, the last rib is about ⅓-turn from edge of outer lip. 
<emphasis id="B942EAC0FA97FF5AC85DBCE6FBCBF9BC" bold="true" box="[869,1059,1533,1558]" italics="true" pageId="242" pageNumber="243">Spiral sculpture</emphasis>
absent. 
<emphasis id="B942EAC0FA97FF5ACFB0BCE6FB3EF9BC" bold="true" box="[1160,1238,1533,1558]" italics="true" pageId="242" pageNumber="243">Sulcus</emphasis>
smooth, without sculpture, flat, not concave. Growth striae, curved reflecting past positions of the anal sinus. 
<emphasis id="B942EAC0FA97FF5ACFA7BF3AFAEEF990" bold="true" box="[1183,1286,1569,1594]" italics="true" pageId="242" pageNumber="243">Outer lip</emphasis>
thin, without axial folds, smooth, edge inrolled from anal sinus to beginning of anterior canal; stromboid notch absent. 
<emphasis id="B942EAC0FA97FF5ACE5CBF5EFF3CF928" bold="true" italics="true" pageId="242" pageNumber="243">Anal sinus</emphasis>
a deep notch on whorl shoulder near suture, edge flared and directed laterally, appearing spout-like. 
<emphasis id="B942EAC0FA97FF5ACE0EBF71FA74F928" bold="true" box="[1334,1436,1641,1666]" italics="true" pageId="242" pageNumber="243">Inner lip</emphasis>
thin, margined, recumbent; extending over apex of aperture with a weak callus at anal sinus. 
<emphasis id="B942EAC0FA97FF5ACF8BBF96FAB4F90C" bold="true" box="[1203,1372,1677,1702]" italics="true" pageId="242" pageNumber="243">Anterior canal</emphasis>
short but well defined, open, unnotched. 
<emphasis id="B942EAC0FA97FF5AC919BFAAFD8AF960" bold="true" box="[545,610,1713,1738]" italics="true" pageId="242" pageNumber="243">Color</emphasis>
translucent white with a light golden brown band mid-whorl, darkened at rib sides.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C32C6559FA97FF5BCBFFBFE1FF23FE2D" lastPageId="243" lastPageNumber="244" pageId="242" pageNumber="243" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="8B8936D2FA97FF5BCBFFBFE1FF23FE2D" blockId="242.[151,1436,1281,2026]" lastBlockId="243.[151,1436,151,464]" lastPageId="243" lastPageNumber="244" pageId="242" pageNumber="243">
<emphasis id="B942EAC0FA97FF5ACBFFBFE1FE28F8BB" bold="true" box="[199,448,1786,1809]" pageId="242" pageNumber="243">
Remarks. 
<emphasis id="B942EAC0FA97FF5ACA7DBFE1FD5AF8B8" box="[325,690,1785,1810]" italics="true" pageId="242" pageNumber="243">
Taxonomy. 
<taxonomicName id="4C364D51FA97FF5ACAF5BFE2FD5AF8B8" box="[461,690,1785,1810]" class="Gastropoda" family="Drilliidae" genus="Lissodrillia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neogastropoda" pageId="242" pageNumber="243" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="fasciata">Lissodrillia fasciata</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
</emphasis>
has the characteristics of the genus: a small glossy shell with a short anterior canal that lacks spiral sculpture. Unlike most of its congeners, the sulcus is devoid of ribs, which are also quite short for the genus, not extending much past the periphery of the whorl 
<taxonomicName id="4C364D51FA97FF5ACF5EBE5AFB02F8F0" box="[1126,1258,1857,1882]" class="Gastropoda" family="Drilliidae" genus="Splendrillia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neogastropoda" pageId="242" pageNumber="243" phylum="Mollusca" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B942EAC0FA97FF5ACF5EBE5AFB02F8F0" box="[1126,1258,1857,1882]" italics="true" pageId="242" pageNumber="243">Splendrillia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
-like. Unlike in 
<taxonomicName id="4C364D51FA97FF5ACBAFBE7EFEF4F8D4" box="[151,284,1893,1918]" class="Gastropoda" family="Drilliidae" genus="Splendrillia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neogastropoda" pageId="242" pageNumber="243" phylum="Mollusca" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B942EAC0FA97FF5ACBAFBE7EFEF4F8D4" box="[151,284,1893,1918]" italics="true" pageId="242" pageNumber="243">Splendrillia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
though, this species lacks spiral sculpture and posses a different anal sinus. 
<emphasis id="B942EAC0FA97FF5ACF56BE7EFAFAF8D4" bold="true" box="[1134,1298,1893,1918]" italics="true" pageId="242" pageNumber="243">Identification.</emphasis>
The species is differentiated from its congeners by its tall narrow spire (overall W/L = 
<number id="3DFE24F5FA97FF5AC8EFBE92FBF0F80B" box="[983,1048,1929,1953]" pageId="242" pageNumber="243" value="0.361">0.361</number>
, which is on the narrow end of the range of its congeners), light golden brown mid-whorl band, and flat sulcus that lacks sculpture. It is most similar to 
<taxonomicName id="4C364D51FA97FF5ACB8FBEC9FE2EF840" authority="Dall, 1881" authorityName="Dall" authorityYear="1881" box="[183,454,2001,2026]" class="Gastropoda" family="Drilliidae" genus="Lissodrillia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neogastropoda" pageId="242" pageNumber="243" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="verrillii">
<emphasis id="B942EAC0FA97FF5ACB8FBEC9FEC5F840" box="[183,301,2001,2026]" italics="true" pageId="242" pageNumber="243">L. verrillii</emphasis>
(Dall, 
<number id="3DFE24F5FA97FF5ACABBBECAFE55F840" box="[387,445,2001,2026]" pageId="242" pageNumber="243" value="1881.0">1881</number>
)
</taxonomicName>
, which also has convex whorls and a bare sulcus, but that species has more convex whorls, is smaller, and lacks the color band. The strongly convex whorls of 
<taxonomicName id="4C364D51FA96FF5BCF19B983FB74FF1A" box="[1057,1180,151,176]" class="Gastropoda" family="Drilliidae" genus="Lissodrillia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neogastropoda" pageId="243" pageNumber="244" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="fasciata">
<emphasis id="B942EAC0FA96FF5BCF19B983FB74FF1A" box="[1057,1180,151,176]" italics="true" pageId="243" pageNumber="244">L. fasciata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are reminiscent of 
<taxonomicName id="4C364D51FA96FF5BCEBDB983FF00FF7F" class="Gastropoda" family="Drilliidae" genus="Lissodrillia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neogastropoda" pageId="243" pageNumber="244" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="turgida" status="new species">
<emphasis id="B942EAC0FA96FF5BCEBDB983FF00FF7F" italics="true" pageId="243" pageNumber="244">L. turgida</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicNameLabel id="A27157BBFA96FF5BCBCEB9A6FE96FF7F" box="[246,382,188,213]" pageId="243" pageNumber="244" rank="species">new species</taxonomicNameLabel>
but that species is smaller (
<quantity id="4CCE9B37FA96FF5BC98FB9A7FCF4FF7E" box="[695,796,188,213]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.72" pageId="243" pageNumber="244" unit="mm" value="4.72">4.72 mm</quantity>
average total length), lacks the flat sulcus, and has more convex ribs. 
<taxonomicName id="4C364D51FA96FF5BCA0DB9C4FDF6FF52" box="[309,542,223,248]" class="Gastropoda" family="Drilliidae" genus="Lissodrillia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neogastropoda" pageId="243" pageNumber="244" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="fasciata">
<emphasis id="B942EAC0FA96FF5BCA0DB9C4FDF6FF52" box="[309,542,223,248]" italics="true" pageId="243" pageNumber="244">Lissodrillia fasciata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is somewhat similar in form to 
<emphasis id="B942EAC0FA96FF5BC88FB9FBFBCBFF5D" box="[951,1059,224,247]" italics="true" pageId="243" pageNumber="244">
<taxonomicName id="4C364D51FA96FF5BC88FB9FBFBF7FF5D" box="[951,1055,224,247]" class="Gastropoda" family="Drilliidae" genus="Lissodrillia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neogastropoda" pageId="243" pageNumber="244" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="vitrea" status="new species">L. vitrea</taxonomicName>
,
</emphasis>
<taxonomicNameLabel id="A27157BBFA96FF5BCF0AB9FBFB28FF52" box="[1074,1216,223,248]" pageId="243" pageNumber="244" rank="species">new species</taxonomicNameLabel>
but is larger, has proportionally shorter ribs, and light golden brown mid-whorl band, which is absent in 
<taxonomicName id="4C364D51FA96FF5BCF4EB81EFB3CFEB6" box="[1142,1236,261,284]" class="Gastropoda" family="Drilliidae" genus="Lissodrillia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neogastropoda" pageId="243" pageNumber="244" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="vitrea">
<emphasis id="B942EAC0FA96FF5BCF4EB81EFB3CFEB6" box="[1142,1236,261,284]" italics="true" pageId="243" pageNumber="244">L. vitrea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. The single wellpreserved 
<typeStatus id="548D8870FA96FF5BCA37B833FED7FE95" box="[271,319,296,319]" pageId="243" pageNumber="244">type</typeStatus>
specimen has distinctly different morphological characteristics from its congeners as described above. 
<collectingCountry id="F3217642FA96FF5BCBDFB857FEEEFECE" box="[231,262,332,356]" name="American Samoa" pageId="243" pageNumber="244">As</collectingCountry>
the sole representative of the genus in the southeastern Caribbean it was felt that it merited description as new.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C32C6559FA96FF5BCBFFB88EFCC2FE7A" pageId="243" pageNumber="244" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="8B8936D2FA96FF5BCBFFB88EFCC2FE7A" blockId="243.[151,1436,151,464]" pageId="243" pageNumber="244">
<emphasis id="B942EAC0FA96FF5BCBFFB88EFEA6FE06" bold="true" box="[199,334,405,428]" pageId="243" pageNumber="244">Etymology.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName id="4C364D51FA96FF5BCA67B88FFDA3FE07" box="[351,587,404,429]" class="Gastropoda" family="Drilliidae" genus="Lissodrillia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neogastropoda" pageId="243" pageNumber="244" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="fasciata">
<emphasis id="B942EAC0FA96FF5BCA67B88FFDA3FE07" box="[351,587,404,429]" italics="true" pageId="243" pageNumber="244">Lissodrillia fasciata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, the Banded 
<taxonomicName id="4C364D51FA96FF5BC9C6B88FFC97FE07" box="[766,895,404,429]" class="Gastropoda" family="Drilliidae" genus="Lissodrillia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neogastropoda" pageId="243" pageNumber="244" phylum="Mollusca" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B942EAC0FA96FF5BC9C6B88FFC97FE07" box="[766,895,404,429]" italics="true" pageId="243" pageNumber="244">Lissodrillia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from the Latin adjective 
<taxonomicName id="4C364D51FA96FF5BCFE9B88FFAC2FE07" box="[1233,1322,404,429]" class="Gastropoda" family="Drilliidae" genus="Lissodrillia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neogastropoda" pageId="243" pageNumber="244" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="fasciata">
<emphasis id="B942EAC0FA96FF5BCFE9B88FFAC2FE07" box="[1233,1322,404,429]" italics="true" pageId="243" pageNumber="244">fasciata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
meaning possessing a band, a reference to its mid-whorl color band.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
